igious leaders in scholarship and public discourse, Moultrie revises modern understandings of how race, gender, and sexual identities interact with religious practice and organization in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAfrican American lesbiansvInterviews2DLC. 0aAfrican American lesbiansvInterviews. 0aAfrican American women clergyvInterviews2DLC. 0aAfrican American women clergyvInterviews. 0aLeadershipxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States2DLC. 0aLeadershipxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aSexual orientationxReligious aspects2DLC. 0aSexual orientationxReligious aspects. 0aWomanismxReligious aspects2DLC. 0aWomanismxReligious aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023746?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023746423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023746/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles